<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10071291722339></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10071291722339><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=10071291722339>RE: The lull line of spells</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=10071291722339#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=83710><span id=Scholar>jcasetnl</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>153 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Nov 30th 9:06 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.54]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ah, more good advice.&nbsp;&nbsp;My personal experience is that this spell cannot be relied on.  It may keep one or two mobs from agro'ing when you're pulling, so instead of getting five you get three.  But the line I draw is at whether or not I could handle them *without* soothe at all.  In other words, it would be *nice* to get only three, but if we get five we aren't in a huge amount of trouble.  But would I walk into a hornet's nest of blues and attempt to soothe everything so I could solo?  No way.  <br><br>As ineffective as it is, I wish it were at least low resist because if it's resisted the mob ussually agros.  <br><br>On the other hand, like you I've found it to work best on greens.  In dungeons this can go a good way to preventing swarms.  As a pally this is especially a problem with undead.  <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

</ul>

